headline: Fed expected to 'stick to the mandate' amid DOJ investigation
summary: President Trump's Department of Justice (DOJ) has launched a criminal investigation into Federal Reserve Chair Jerome Powell. As earnings season for banks gets underway, JPMorgan Chase (JPM) CEO Jamie Dimon stated that "anything that chips away" at the Fed's independence "is probably not a great idea." Allspring Global Investments chief investment strategist for fixed income George Bory and New Century Advisors chief economist Claudia Sahm — alongside BMO Capital Markets' Jennifer Lee — examine how Fed officials are expected to react to these headlines. Sahm also served as a Federal Reserve Board economist and is the creator of the central bank's Sahm Rule recession indicator. headline: JPMorgan earnings: 3 biggest takeaways
summary: JPMorgan Chase (JPM) reported fourth quarter results that were a bit of a mixed bag for investors. Last week, the bank announced a deal to take over the Apple Card portfolio from Goldman Sachs. That deal weighed on the results. Net income in the quarter was $13 billion, including $2.2 billion in credit losses it planned for as a result of the deal. Net income would have been $14.7 billion in the quarter without the deal. Earnings per share without the costs were $5.23, higher than the $4.85 Wall Street estimates. Including costs from the Apple Card deal, earnings per share were $4.63. Yahoo Finance Executive Editor Brian Sozzi shares his three biggest takeaways from the report and media call. To watch more expert insights and analysis on the latest market action, check out more Morning Brief.

headline: JPMorgan Chase profits rise 9% in the fourth quarter excluding hit from the Apple Card acquisition
summary: JPMorgan Chase said Tuesday that its fourth-quarter profits rose 9% on an adjusted basis, as the bank continues to benefit broadly from a strong economy in both its consumer and investment banking divisions.  The results included a one-time hit of 60 cents per share to its results from JPMorgan Chase’s purchase of the Apple Card credit card portfolio from Goldman Sachs.  This is because the bank added $2.2 billion in loan-loss reserves to its balance sheet to cover the risk of taking on Apple Card, effectively money the bank socks away to cover potential losses.

headline: JPMorgan Investment-Banking Fees Drop on Underwriting Miss
summary: JPMorgan kicks off the industry’s latest round of results Tuesday, with megabank rivals Bank of America Corp., Wells Fargo & Co, Citigroup Inc., Goldman Sachs Group Inc. and Morgan Stanley slated for Wednesday and Thursday.  “The U.S. economy has remained resilient,” Chief Executive Officer Jamie Dimon said in the statement.  With $57 billion of net income for 2025, JPMorgan fell short its 2024 record, which was the highest annual profit in the history of American banking.
